Members of the three Federal Capital Territory (FCT) committees in the national assembly have recommended the use of local languages in the sensitisation of residents on measures towards the prevention of the deadly coronavirus in the territory. Speaking after a meeting between the leadership of the committees and the FCT Administration at the weekend, chairman, House Committee on FCT Area Councils and Ancillary Matters, Hon Ahmed Tijani Damisa, stressed the need for more sensitisation on COVID-19 in the FCT area councils. Speaking earlier, chairman, Senate Committee on the FCT, Senator Abubakar Kyari, had expressed satisfaction with the actions being taken by the FCT Administration in the fight against COVID-19. Senator Kyari, who was the chairman of the meeting, explained that before the interaction, members of the national assembly were a bit concerned about the level of preparedness, adding however that the outcome of the meeting has shown that the administration is on top of their game. Chairman, House Committee on the FCT, Hon Abdullahi Garba, who was part of the meeting, noted that the FCT minister of state, Dr Ramatu Tijjani Aliyu, was doing well in her efforts at sensitising and enlightening residents at the grassroots level on the pandemic, as well as the preparedness being made for the distribution of palliatives. Responding, FCT minister, Malam Muhammad Musa Bello, revealed that the parliamentarians have assured the provision of full legislative support towards the efforts being put in place by the administration. “We have all agreed on measures to be taken and they also assured us of proper legislative support like they have always done and we continue to count on the cooperation with them.” Bello added that the legislators have also agreed that to win the fight against COVID 19, there must be full stakeholders’ engagement, while all arms of government and the citizens have to work together, because the greatest weapon in this fight is personal discipline, adherence to government’s medical regulations and social distancing.  